com.solacesystems.jcsmp

Interface Session

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    JCSMPDestinationSession, JCSMPSession
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    JCSMPBasicSession, SessionModeSupport, SessionModeSupportClient

    public interface Session
    Session represents the main application interface.

    Introduction

    JCSMP is the Java implementation of the Solace Content Subscription Management Protocol (CSMP). It provides a programming interface for applications interacting with a Solace appliance. The following protocol stack is supported: 
    
                             +---------------------------------------+
                             |                 JCSMP                 |
                             +---------------------------------------+
                             |                  CSMP                 |
                             +---------------------------------------+
                             |                  SMF                  |
                             +---------------------------------------+
                             |                TCP/IP                 |
                             +---------------------------------------+
                             
                              (SMF stands for Solace Message Format.)

    Session

    Session provides these major functions:
    • Session lifecycle control, such as initializing and closing.
    • Subscriber management
    • Access to associated statistics.

    A client application uses JCSMPFactory to acquire a JCSMPSession instance by providing JCSMPProperties.

    Note: All methods defined in Session are thread-safe.

    Message Types

    The following message delivery modes can be used for publishing:
    Persistent and Non-Persistent
    The appliance guarantees delivery to subscribers. These messages are always spooled in the Solace Messaging Platform and delivered in order. Refer to XMLMessage for more details.

    Persistent and Non-Persistent messages can only be published over the JCSMPChannelProperties.SUPPORTED_PROTOCOL_STACK_SMF_TCP protocol stack.

    Direct
    Delivery of the document is not guaranteed (the Solace Message Platform uses a best-effort approach to delivery). Direct messages are never spooled to disk on the appliance, and they can be delivered out of order.

    Direct messages can be published over the JCSMPChannelProperties.SUPPORTED_PROTOCOL_STACK_SMF_TCP protocol stack.

    Message Acknowledgement Mode

    Session supports two message acknowledgement modes: AUTO_ACK and CLIENT_ACK. With AUTO_ACK mode, when delivering each message to the application, the session acknowledges the message to the appliance automatically. With CLIENT_ACK, it is the application's responsibility to acknowledge by calling XMLMessage.ackMessage(). It is also the application's responsibility to have a policy in place to enforce in-time acknowledgement of all messages to avoid repeated delivery of Persistent and Non-Persistent messages.

    Exceptions

    There are three categories of exceptions defined in JCSMP:
    • JCSMPOperationException
    • JCSMPTransportException
    • JCSMPStateException
    Please refer to JCSMPException for details.

    • Method Detail

      • getSessionName

        String getSessionName()
        If the session name is specified by JCSMPProperties.SESSION_NAME, this method returns the name specified. Otherwise, a default name is returned.
        Returns:
        The session name.

      • closeSession

        void closeSession()
        Closes the session. Once a session is closed it must not be used again, an application must instead acquire a new session.

        Any XMLMessageProducer, XMLMessageConsumer, and channel connections associated with the session are also closed.

      • isClosed

        boolean isClosed()
        SolReserved - Checks if this session has been closed. Once a session is closed it must not be used again, an application must instead acquire a new session.
        Returns:
        true if the session has been closed, false otherwise.

      • getSessionStats

        JCSMPSessionStats getSessionStats()
        Get this session's statistics.
        Returns:
        The session statistics.

      • logSessionStats

        void logSessionStats(JCSMPLogLevel level)
        Outputs a log at the specified log level containing a textual representation of the session statistics.
        Parameters:
        level - The level (corresponding to org.apache.commons.logging levels) at which to output the log.

      • clearSubscriber

        void clearSubscriber()
                     throws JCSMPException
        Deprecated. This method is no longer supported. The recommended way to delete subscriptions from the appliance is to perform an applySubscriptions() on the session with an empty subscription list.
        Removes a subscriber's CSMP-created subscriptions from the appliance.

        Note that if the subscriber has a large number of subscriptions, this operation can take a long time to return. If your application creates subscribers with several thousand subscriptions, it is advisable to increase the session's response timeout from the default, otherwise this operation could fail while waiting for the appliance to respond.

        Throws:
        JCSMPException - If there was an error clearing the subscriber.
        OperationNotSupportedException - If performed on a closed session or a session not configured for this operation.

      • deleteSubscriber

        void deleteSubscriber()
                      throws JCSMPException
        Throws:
        JCSMPException

      • addSubscriber

        void addSubscriber()
                   throws JCSMPException
        Deprecated. It is no longer necessary to call this function. This function might be removed in a future version of JCSMP.
        Adds a subscriber to the appliance using the user information associated with the Session.

        If the user already exists on the appliance, this method still returns success.

        Throws:
        JCSMPException - If there was an error adding the subscriber.

      • removeSubscriber

        void removeSubscriber()
                      throws JCSMPException
        Deprecated. Subscribers are now created and removed only through the appliance's management interface. This method has the same effect as clearSubscriber()
        Removes a subscriber from the appliance using the user information associated with the Session.
        Throws:
        JCSMPException - If there was an error removing the subscriber.
